By Week 12 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern that had been forming came into sharper relief. Power was no longer only gathered at the center; it was being driven through the country\'92s arteries in new ways, into agencies, courts, universities, and even the tax system. The week\'92s events showed a government that had learned how to use law, money, and fear together, so that each move reinforced the others. Immigration policy, trade wars, and culture fights were no longer separate fronts. They were parts of a single project to redraw who counted, who decided, and who remembered.\
\
On the Democracy Clock, the week opened at 7:35 p.m. and closed at 7:36 p.m., a shift of 0.3 minutes. The movement was small, but it came from many directions at once. Executive power widened again, as emergency trade tools and immigration law were bent into routine instruments of rule. Law was used more openly as a weapon, not a limit. Universities and civil servants were pressed into line or cut loose. Voting rules tightened under the banner of \'93integrity,\'94 while non\uc0\u8209 citizens were pushed further outside the circle of protection. The minute hand moved because these changes were structural, not just symbolic. They made it harder for other institutions to say no.\
\
The most visible shock of the week was economic. Trump\'92s tariff regime, launched as \'93Liberation Day,\'94 deepened and then lurched sideways. Sweeping tariffs on nearly every trading partner had already wiped trillions from U.S. markets, with losses of $5\'966 trillion in stock value and sharp drops in major indices. New orders raised duties on Chinese imports to triple\uc0\u8209 digit levels, with one executive order pushing effective rates to 145% when combined with a fentanyl\u8209 linked surcharge. Another order amended the tariff schedule to lift Chinese rates to 84% and clamp down on low\u8209 value postal imports. These moves were justified under the International Emergency Economic Powers Act, a law meant for national security crises, not long\u8209 term tax policy. The White House insisted this was about \'93reciprocity\'94 and national defense. In practice, it meant the president was setting the country\'92s trade taxes alone.\
