Markets reacted with wild swings. Rumors of a tariff pause sent stocks soaring, only to crash again when the White House denied them. After days of turmoil, Trump announced a 90\uc0\u8209 day pause on some tariffs, but kept a 10% blanket duty on most imports and raised China\'92s rate even higher. The pause was framed as strategic, yet it underscored how much economic life now hinged on a single person\'92s statements. Corporations that might once have pushed back stayed quiet, with reporting that major firms feared retaliation if they spoke out. Economic data and expert warnings\'97from the Federal Reserve, investment banks, and trade economists\'97were brushed aside or distorted. In this domain, the winners were those closest to the decision\u8209 maker: favored industries, donors, and firms able to ride or game the volatility. The losers were diffuse: workers, consumers, and trading partners who had no seat at the table and no clear recourse.\
