Congress tried, in part, to reassert itself over this new economic emergency rule. Senators from both parties introduced bills to require congressional approval for new tariffs and to reclaim the legislature\'92s constitutional role over trade. A bipartisan amendment to reverse tariffs on Canadian imports passed the Senate. House and Senate hearings probed the use of emergency law for routine economic policy, and even conservative voices at National Review urged Congress to \'93reclaim power\'94 ceded to the presidency. Yet at the same time, House Republican leaders used procedural rules to block a floor vote on disapproving Trump\'92s tariff emergency. A budget framework that would enable large tax cuts and add trillions to the debt passed on a narrow partisan margin. The net effect was that Congress signaled concern but left the core structure of unilateral tariff power intact. Legislative resistance existed, but it was fragmented and often symbolic, while the executive\'92s use of emergency tools became more normal.\
