The same pattern appeared in the treatment of law itself. Over the week, the administration issued and defended executive orders aimed not at general policy, but at specific legal adversaries. One set of orders targeted law firms that had represented Trump\'92s political rivals or litigated against his interests, including the firm that helped secure Dominion Voting Systems\'92 settlement with Fox News. These orders stripped lawyers of security clearances, barred them from federal buildings, and threatened their ability to represent clients before the government. Other firms, facing similar threats, negotiated deals: they agreed to provide hundreds of millions of dollars in pro bono work for causes favored by Trump, to avoid race\uc0\u8209 conscious hiring, and to represent \'93politically disenfranchised\'94 groups defined by the administration. In exchange, the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission dropped inquiries into their diversity practices, and the White House held back harsher orders. Law became a bargaining chip. Access to the state\'92s legal machinery was conditioned on political compliance.\
