Universities and knowledge institutions became another central battleground. The administration had already pulled $400 million in federal funding from Columbia University over its handling of pro\uc0\u8209 Palestinian protests, demanding bans on masks, expanded arrest powers for campus security, and direct control over Middle East studies. This week, Columbia\'92s president resigned, and the university accepted the conditions to restore funding. The Justice Department considered placing the school under a consent decree, which would bind it to a court\u8209 approved plan overseen by federal lawyers. Similar funding freezes hit Cornell and Northwestern, with over $1.7 billion in grants and contracts suspended on claims that the schools had failed to protect Jewish students or had tolerated \'93divisive\'94 ideologies. The administration also paused funding to the University of Pennsylvania over its inclusion of transgender athletes. The message was clear. Federal money would flow only to institutions that aligned their speech, hiring, and protest policies with the White House\'92s preferences.\
