Citizenship itself became more stratified. Non\uc0\u8209 citizens, especially from targeted countries like Venezuela and South Sudan, faced visa revocations, travel bans, and deportations under old wartime laws. International students and green\u8209 card holders involved in pro\u8209 Palestinian activism were arrested, detained, or threatened with deportation under provisions that framed them as foreign\u8209 policy threats. A Palestinian graduate from Columbia, Mahmoud Khalil, remained in detention in Louisiana while the administration sought to deport him under a rarely used statute, claiming his activism aligned with Hamas. An immigration judge demanded that DHS produce evidence or face ordering his release, but the case showed how easily political dissent could be recast as a security risk when citizenship was conditional. Even within the citizenry, lines hardened. Policies that cut funding to a state corrections department because it housed a trans woman in a women\'92s prison, or that ordered the State Department to catalogue \'93anti\u8209 Christian bias\'94 under the previous administration, signaled that some identities and beliefs would be favored, others penalized.\
