Yet even these acts of resistance unfolded in a landscape shaped by chaos. The week\'92s events did not form a single, clean story. They came as overlapping shocks: tariff announcements and reversals; executive orders on coal, water pressure, and shipbuilding; firings at the NSA and NATO posts; new military budgets and plans for a June military parade; purges at NOAA and climate programs; investigations into children\'92s entertainers and non\uc0\u8209 profits; and a memo authorizing the military to take over public lands along the southern border and detain migrants until ICE arrived. Each move had its own justification\'97national security, energy reliability, religious freedom, anti\u8209 corruption, child safety. Together, they pulled attention in many directions at once. This fragmentation was not just a side effect. It made it harder for Congress, courts, and the public to track any single line of change, and easier for the executive to keep moving.\
