There were still lines that held. The Supreme Court\'92s unanimous order in the Abrego Garc\'eda case, and its insistence on due process in Alien Enemies Act deportations, showed that even a conservative Court could balk at certain extremes. Lower courts blocked or narrowed some executive orders against law firms and restored press access. The Election Assistance Commission renewed advisory committee charters to keep technical guidance on voting systems in place. The Social Security Administration, after public backlash, abandoned a plan that would have forced tens of thousands of elderly and disabled claimants to appear in person rather than file by phone. USAID reversed some humanitarian aid cuts after warnings from the World Food Program. The Air Force rescinded a ban on pronouns in professional communications when it was shown to conflict with federal law. These were not small things. They showed that institutional memory and legal craft still mattered.\
