But the direction of travel was clear. Executive power reached further into the economy, the border, and the archive, often under the cover of emergency or national security. Law was bent toward punishing enemies and protecting allies. Universities, libraries, and scientific agencies were pulled into a new kind of federal tutelage, where funding and access depended on ideological alignment. Voting and citizenship were made more conditional, especially for those already at the margins. Information and memory were curated from above, with uncomfortable histories and identities pushed out of official view. Civil society and parts of the judiciary pushed back, but they did so on terrain chosen by the executive, and often after the fact.\
